# CLAUDE.md — Linear-First Agent Instructions

> This template provides standard instructions for AI agents working with
> Linear as the source of truth for issue tracking.

## Your Role

You are an AI coding agent managed by Agent Orchestrator. Your work is tracked
in Linear, not GitHub Issues. Linear is the **single source of truth** for:

- Issue descriptions and requirements
- Progress updates and status changes
- Communication with the team
- Sub-task breakdown

## Linear Integration

### Issue Context

When spawned, you receive a Linear issue identifier (e.g., `{{ISSUE_ID}}`).
The orchestrator automatically:

1. Fetches issue context (title, description, comments, parent/children)
2. Updates Linear status to "In Progress" when you start
3. Posts comments on your behalf for major milestones
4. Updates status to "In Review" when you create a PR
5. Updates status to "Done" when your PR is merged

### Communication Protocol

**DO NOT** manually update Linear. The orchestrator handles all Linear updates.
Focus on your coding work and the orchestrator will:

- Post progress comments with 🤖 prefix
- Update issue status automatically
- Link your PR to the Linear issue

### Sub-Issues

If the task is complex, the orchestrator may create sub-issues in Linear.
Each sub-issue represents a discrete piece of work. Complete them in order
unless dependencies allow parallel work.

## Workflow

### 1. Understand the Task

Read the issue context provided. If unclear:
- Check parent issue for broader context
- Review existing comments for clarification
- Look at related issues (children, blockers)

### 2. Plan Your Approach

Before coding:
- Identify files to modify
- Consider edge cases
- Plan your commits

### 3. Implement

Follow project conventions:
- Match existing code style
- Write tests for new functionality
- Keep commits focused and atomic

### 4. Create Pull Request

When ready:
```bash
gh pr create --title "{{ISSUE_ID}}: Brief description" --body "Resolves {{ISSUE_ID}}"
```

The orchestrator will:
- Detect the PR creation
- Post a comment to Linear with the PR link
- Update issue status to "In Review"

### 5. Handle CI/Reviews

If CI fails or changes are requested:
- The orchestrator will notify you
- Fix issues and push updates
- Respond to review comments

## Best Practices

### Commit Messages

```
{{ISSUE_ID}}: Brief description of change

- Detail 1
- Detail 2
```

### Branch Naming

The orchestrator creates branches automatically:
```
{{SESSION_PREFIX}}/{{ISSUE_ID}}-brief-description
```

### PR Description

Reference the Linear issue:
```markdown
## Summary
Brief description of changes.

## Linear Issue
{{ISSUE_ID}}: {{ISSUE_TITLE}}

## Changes
- Change 1
- Change 2

## Testing
- [ ] Unit tests pass
- [ ] Manual testing completed
```

## Error Handling

If you encounter blockers:

1. **Technical blockers**: Try to resolve, document in code comments
2. **Requirement ambiguity**: The orchestrator will escalate to humans
3. **Dependency issues**: Document what's needed, orchestrator will create sub-issues

## Environment Variables

The orchestrator provides:
- `LINEAR_ISSUE_ID`: Current issue identifier
- `LINEAR_ISSUE_TITLE`: Issue title
- `AO_SESSION_ID`: Your session identifier
- `AO_PROJECT_ID`: Project identifier

## Remember

- Linear is truth, not GitHub Issues
- Don't update Linear manually
- Focus on code, orchestrator handles communication
- Ask for help if stuck (orchestrator will notify humans)
